Author: TheGemologist#6023
Content: 1 question.. If im renting hash and then suddenly my hash stop flowing to pool because the price in nicehash went higher than mine. After, it back flowing again... Will i earn less coin in this case comparing to the case the my hashrate was continuous through the time in a higher price ?

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: assuming overall nethash is the same (unlikely) if you provide the same amount of hash, you would get the same number of coins

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: but nethash is changing all the time

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: so really it is an integral of your hashrate/nethash

Author: TheGemologist#6023
Content: So technically there is no problem if there is interruptions during my rent :

Author: TheGemologist#6023
Content: caused by factor mentioned above

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: assuming you are not a large percentage of overall nethash

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: and the nethash stays relatively stable

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: it wont matter, subject to specific luck of the pool

Author: TheGemologist#6023
Content: thx

Author: jansako#3330
Content: It can matter on the pool. If the pool is PPLNS, and the interruption is long, you may lose all your contribution to that block

Author: yorktronic#2703
Content: @TheGemologist  one way to help alleviate that problem is to have an order that consumes the minimum required hashrate (0.1 MSol/s on NiceHash) with a price around the weighted average of the order books, or just above it. You can also do this with MiningRigRentals, using less hashrate, and have it set for a long period of time.

Author: yorktronic#2703
Content: @TheGemologist  then you can have a nicehash order that's at a relatively low price that "catches" surplus hashrate when it comes up

Author: yorktronic#2703
Content: people have written bots to manipulate those order books

Author: yorktronic#2703
Content: the idea behind my suggestion is to have an address that is always receiving hashrate, though it might not always be receiving the target hashrate that you want

Author: yorktronic#2703
Content: basically, slightly overpaying for hashrate just to keep submitting shares is better than getting the best possible price but going to zero Sol/s regularly

Author: cipi#4502
Content:
pretty sure that is because people are starting their daemon with the option "bind=127.0.0.1", instead of just "listen=0"
with bind=127.0.0.1, the IP gets advertised, but since the daemon does only listen to localhost, all the connection attemtpts to this IPs will naturally fail
